<p>Accountancy is a highly-skilled and highly-disciplined field, which is why good Accountants remain in demand across the UK. Research shows that the country will need around 80,000 additional Accountants by 2050.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Do you need to be good at maths to be an accountant and financial adviser/officer?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Practical knowledge of maths, especially algebra and arithmetic are generally sufficient to become a good accountant. The only math that you need to know to become a good accountant is being able to measure analysing the transactions before recording it.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Can I be an accountant or financial adviser if I'm bad at math?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Accounting programs usually require business and management courses, as well as statistics. While some degrees may require a higher math course, it's lower math operations and basic algebra that will help you most. So if you struggled through calculus in high school or managed to avoid it entirely, don't despair.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Which degree is better, accounting or finance?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>So finance degree students will likely be more interested in financial strategy and control. In contrast, accounting degree students will be more focused on professional principles and processes, used to manage numbers rather than influence them.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Can I become an accountant with a finance degree?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Yes, people with Economics and Finance degrees can become CPAs if they meet the minimum educational and work experience requirements that we talked about above, but it's not easy. Most Econ and Finance majors don't take many accounting classes in college.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What type of training do you need to be an accountant or financial adviser?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Most accountants and financial advisers need at least a bachelor's degree in business, accounting, or a related field. Many accountants and auditors choose to obtain certification to help advance their careers, such as becoming a Certified Public Accountant (CPA).</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How can I teach myself accounting and finance studies?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>To learn accounting and finance on your own, start by reading books on the subject and familiarising yourself with how to create finance spreadsheets. Practice necessary accounting skills like recording debits and credits and setting up and maintaining ledgers.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the difference between an accountant and a financial advisor?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Accountants do auditing work, financial forecasting, and putting together financial statements. In contrast, financial planners help individuals with wealth management and retirement planning. Accountants are usually detail-oriented and good with numbers, while financial planners are better at sales and networking.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Can you be a financial advisor with an accounting degree?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>A minimum of a bachelor's degree is usually required to become a personal financial advisor. However, no specific degree speciality is necessary, so students with degrees in areas such as accounting, finance, mathematics and economics are eligible.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the five basic accounting principles?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Five principles of accounting are:</p>
<li> Revenue recognition principle,</li>
<li> Historical cost principle,</li>
<li> Matching principle,</li>
<li> Full disclosure principle, and.</li>
<li> Objectivity principle.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the basic accounting equation?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The accounting equation is the foundation of the double-entry accounting system. The accounting equation shows on a company's balance sheet whereby the total of all the company's assets equals the sum of the company's liabilities and shareholders' equity.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the three golden rules of accounting?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The golden rules of accounting:</p>
<li> Debit the receiver, credit the giver. This principle is useful in the case of personal accounts.</li>
<li> Debit what comes in, credit what goes out. This principle will apply in case of real accounts.</li>
<li> Debit all expenses and losses, credit all incomes and gains.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the different types of accounting?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The different types of accounting:</p>
<li> Financial accounting</li>
<li> Governmental accounting</li>
<li> Public accounting</li>
<li> Cost accounting</li>
<li> Forensic accounting</li>
<li> Management accounting</li>
<li> Tax accounting</li>
<li> Auditing.</li>
